                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Paradigm shifts are always painful -- see negative reviews</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-29</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I am not surprised by the negative reviews for this book.  Notice how many individuals attack Emoto's integrity and objectivity yet these same critics exhibit such a strong emotional aversion to the book.  After all, I didn't notice any thoughtful rebuttals of his ideas, only sarcasm and mockery.  Does anyone see the hypocrisy in this?  While Emoto's explanations for his observations are certainly not substantiated, we should not dismiss them simply because they lack a mechanistic explanation.  Being that our scientific efforts have shown even the most "rational" thinking to involve the highly emotional centers of the brain (limbic system), I am reluctant to say that there is a purely rational, objective form of thinking.  However, we can still strive, and anyone that dismisses the possible implications of this book is probably doing so for emotional reasons.  What would your mechanistic, reductionist colleagues think of YOU if you were to actually humor Emoto?
<br />
<br />On another philosophical note, I have pondered what might happen if these water crystal-type experiments were subjected to true scientific scrutiny.  I would not be surprised if the correlations presented herein broke down.  Look at it this way: these experiments would essentially attempt to capture intent.  Should the scientific community find out about the details of such experiments, there would be what I will call a "consciousness tug-of-war" between skeptical minds and hopeful minds.  Larry Dossey speaks of nonlocal mind and the ability of our intent to influence others (i.e. distance healing, hexes).  Those with absolutely no expectations would be the only ones who wouldn't exert an influence over the experimental outcomes.  Regrettably, as I perceive it, the skeptical minds would likely prevail as they seem greater in number (at least within the scientific community).  If the public were to find out about such experiments, they might tip the scales in favor of positive outcomes as I think a greater proportion of vitalistic, spiritual people are represented among laypeople...
<br />
<br />What you should gather from this convolted scenario is the fact that certain things are simply too subtle, complex, and nonlinear to be captured/measured/appreciated by scientific study.  Intent may prove to be one of them.  David Hawkins and others who calibrate intent are exceptions to this assertion, although many conventional scientists discredit this calibration method entirely.  What virtually all scientists fail to recognize is that science yields a representation of reality, a model or worldview.  There are alternate worldviews that are arguably as valid.  Many of you have likely heard "The Scientist" by Coldplay, known for its memorable piano arrangement.  If you haven't already, now would be a good time to pay close attention to the lyrics!</span>
                  
